---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import HelpCallout from "../../components/HelpCallout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="For families & loved ones"
  description="How to recognize gambling harm in someone you love, how to talk about it, how to protect yourself, and where to find support."
>
  <header class="page-header">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="page-header__eyebrow">
        <a href="/understand-gambling">← Understand gambling</a>
      </p>
      <h1>For families &amp; loved ones</h1>
      <p class="page-header__lead">
        When someone you love is struggling with gambling, it affects you too. You
        are not alone, and support is available for you as well as for them.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container prose">
      <h2>Signs you might notice</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Money or valuables going missing, or unexplained debt</li>
        <li>Being secretive about finances or whereabouts</li>
        <li>Borrowing money often, or asking to "cover" expenses</li>
        <li>Mood swings tied to wins and losses</li>
        <li>Pulling away from family time or responsibilities</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How to talk about it</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Pick a calm, private time — not right after a loss.</li>
        <li>Speak from care: "I've noticed… and I'm worried about you."</li>
        <li>Avoid blame and labels. Person-first language helps: "someone with a gambling problem," not "a gambler" or "an addict."</li>
        <li>Listen more than you lecture. Change is more likely when someone feels supported.</li>
        <li>Have the helpline ready so a next step is easy.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Protect yourself and your finances</h2>
      <p>
        You are not responsible for another adult's gambling, and you cannot
        control it for them. You can set boundaries — including with money. Many
        families find it helps to separate or protect their finances and to seek
        their own support. This is not giving up on the person; it is taking care
        of yourself so you can keep helping.
      </p>

      <h2>Get support — for them and for you</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>The National Problem Gambling Helpline can guide both of you to local resources.</li>
        <li>Family support groups such as <a href="https://www.gam-anon.org/">Gam-Anon</a> connect you with others who understand.</li>
        <li>If anyone is in crisis or thinking about suicide, call or text <a href="tel:988">988</a> any time.</li>
      </ul>

      <HelpCallout />

      <div class="sources">
        <h2>Learn more</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="https://www.gam-anon.org/">Gam-Anon (family support)</a></li>
          <li><a href="https://www.ncpgambling.org/">National Council on Problem Gambling</a></li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
